Here is my answer, although I'm probably retarded. The numbers aren't clean which is a huge red flag.
There are 4 forces acting on the car at point C; the braking force, the centripetal force, normal force, and gravity. Assuming the road is flat, gravity and the normal force cancel out. That leaves us the braking force and centripetal force.
There are two tricky parts to this problem, the first is that we are given a changing acceleration, so the kinematic equations is going to be less plug and play. Secondly, we have to solve for the radius of the arc.

Rearranging the kinematics eqn, we get the following:
-1/48*t^3 + 30*t - 100 = 0 where the only valid answer of t (between 0 and 15) is 3.35967 seconds. (I used an online calculator to solve the cubic)

We are now able to figure out the new acceleration and velocity at point B, which is -0.42 m/s^2 (plug time into the acceleration function) and 20.29m/s .

Now from B to C, we know we have 11.64s to get there. We can then just plug that value into our kinematic eqn:

-1/48 (11.64)^3 + -0.42(11.64)^2 + 29.2944(11.64) + 0 = 251.225 m

We will also need to find the velocity at C which is:
(-1/16)(11.64^2) +(-1/8)*11.64 + 29.2944 = 19.3713 m/s

Now we need the radius of the arc:
251m/0.785 = 320.0m

Finally we can compute the centrifugal acceleration:
(19.373)^2/320.0 = 1.173m/s^2

The other force (braking) is more straight forward to compute:
-1/8*15 = -1.875 m/s^2
Now, the brakes are applying the force tangent to the circle, while the centrifugal force is pointing towards the center of the circle. This basically means that the two forces are perpendicular to one another, so to sum the total acceleration, we are going need use a^2 + b^2 = c^2.

sqrt(1.875^2 +1.173^2) = 2.211 m/s^2

>>29475794
I have 1a hair. To be clear, this type of hair is already low maintenance and naturally straight.

Layered haircuts is a good start.
If you see frizz, usually it's too many split ends or dry hair. Get a trim or use oil/leave-in conditioner to treat these respectively.

I wash my hair every 2-3 days, any more and you strip too much of your natural oils which keeps your hair hydrated and looking nice. This is not a hard rule, if your hair starts feeling really greasy/dirty/weighed down, just wash it.
I really liked using OGX coconut oil shampoo for a long time, but recently switched to Jupiter pythrione zinc shampoo because it helps my skin condition. But in general I think any sulfate-free shampoo is a good pick, again trying to preserve your scalp's natural oils.
Shampooing is root to end, make sure you massage the scalp too. You may want to look into a scalp massager you keep in the shower to help with this. Rinse ALL of the shampoo out when you're done.

For conditioner I kind of just do whatever, I switch up a lot. My hair type lets me be pretty flexible on conditioner imo, but you may want to get something more specific to your needs.
Applying the conditioner goes from the middle of your hair strands to the ends. DO NOT do the roots. This unnecessarily weighs down your hair and makes it hard to achieve volume. It also makes it hard for your roots to absorb scalp oils. Now, leave the conditioner in for 5-15m before rinsing it out. I usually wash my body during this time.

After I shower I try to pat my hair dry with my towel. I also untangle my hair with a comb, depending on your hair type you might like a brush more. If your strands are more brittle you may want to consider wrapping them in a towel or t-shirt.
When I'm done with my skincare routine I roughly style/set my hair (while it's wet) in the way I want it to look for the next couple of days. Usually a combination of comb or touseling with fingers.

(cont) You can use hair clips to hooks stubborn strands in place. Your hair should maintain that shape while it's wet, and roughly once it dries.
Using a blowdryer is excellent for setting hair, but I generally don't use one because I'm bad at it.

In the south we had Selk'nams and Aonikenk, the latter of which were very tall in height (the Spanish said they were 6'8" tall, most probably they were around 5'11" or 6' on average, still extremely tall for 1500s standards) and the Patagonia region (southern half of Argentina) was named after them (Patagonia means 'Land of Giants'). To the southwest we have Mapuches (my ancestors uwu), who are known for being very brave and the only indigenous peoples the Spanish could not conquer.

To the northeast we have Qom people, Guaraníes and there used to be Payaguás, very fiery people that kept the Spanish from exploring our rivers for years.

Helping friends Edition
previous: >>29406341

Goal of the thread: Work on one skill you wish to be better at. It can be as simple as reading a small paragraph of a text book on the subject.
Daily goals can be repeated. Remember to keep score, it can only go up!

>What is this thread for?
Getting better is hard, and sucks. A lot. It does not get easier doing it alone.
Share resources and experiences with combating depression, anxiety, personal issues, achieving or maintaining a healthy weight, etc.
>Why is this thread /lgbt/?
Struggles with mental and physical health are an indisputable part of /lgbt/ life, be it from dysphoria, social pressure, heartbreak, or just unfortunate lifestyle choices.
>Notes to consider:
Please be civil. Shame is your greatest enemy in fighting urges of self abuse (be it sh, drugs, or just self deprecation). Relapsing into bad and unhealthy habits is to be expected, the goal is to increase the average amount of time it takes between relapses. Any improvement is a victory no matter how small. Your worth and right to get better are non-negotiable. And most importantly:
WE ARE NOT THERAPISTS, WE DON'T REPLACE MEDICATION
>Note on advice
Generic advice won't necessarily help you in particular, but for those it does it is an essential foundation to build future progress on, not a miracle cure. Do not underestimate the effects subtle changes to your lifestyle can have. Try first, keep us posted on your progress, build from there.

We are *always* short on self help resources, so if anything was useful to you, let us know!
Since the OP is getting too long I moved all resources into their own post, see below!

What I mean by "plan, measure, adjust" is that you should never expect the initial schedule to be realistic. You can always do more than you planned: It just feels better to over perform on a day rather than under perform, so a conservative estimate is better. Once you planed, you actually stick to with with some flexibility and see whether you find yourself consistently doing more than planned. Also account for rest and sick days, your 3 reserve days are an excellent idea.

The integral of 1/1 + x from 0 to 1 is less than pi/4, so there must be some x1 such that 1/1 + x1 < f(x1). ٓAdditionally, since the integral from epsilon to 1 diverges to positive infinity as epsilon approaches 0, the area underneath 1/2x is decidedly larger than the area under f(x) on the interval (0, 1), so there must be some x2 in (0, 1) for which f(x2) < 1/2x2. Assuming that neither of these are solutions would mean that f(x1) > 1/2x1 and f(x2) < 1/1 + x2, but because f is continuous, f(x) must take every value between f(x1) and f(x2) on the interval (x1, x2)/(x2, x1) (depending on which is greater). Since 1/1+x and 1/2x do not intersect on the interval (0, 1), this means that f(x) must cross a gap at some point in between these values, and in this gap there must be some x0 where 1/1+x0 < f(x0) < 1/2x0. There might be a flaw somewhere in this proof, and I used a graphing calculator to visualize it so maybe that’s cheating, but this is my final answer.
